ross both ODI and T20I formats.<ref name=\"Ind-Pak\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/985651.html|title=Kohli special steers India home on a turner|access-date=20 March 2016|work=ESPN Cricinfo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320190308/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/985651.html|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''[[Ahmed Shehzad]] became the fifth player for Pakistan to pass 1,000 runs in T20Is.<ref name=\"Shehzad\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/985861.html|title=The king of the run chase|access-date=20 March 2016|work=ESPN Cricinfo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321103136/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/985861.html|archive-date=21 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n----\n\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = {{anchor|match28}} 26 March\n| time = 15:00\n| daynight = Yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|NZ}}\n| team2 = {{cr|BAN}}\n| score1 = 145/8 (20 overs)\n| score2 = 70 (15.4 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Kane Williamson]] 42 (32)\n| wickets1 = [[Mustafizur Rahman]] 5/22 (4 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Shuvagata Hom]] 16[[not out|*]] (17)\n| wickets2 = [[Grant Elliott]] 3/12 (4 overs)\n| toss = New Zealand won the toss and elected to bat.\n| motm = [[Kane Williamson]] (NZ)\n| umpires = [[Johan Cloete]] (SA) and [[Michael Gough (cricketer)|Michael Gough]] (Eng)\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/951359.html Scorecard]\n| result = {{cr|New Zealand}} won by 75 runs\n| notes = [[Henry Nicholls (cricketer)|Henry Nicholls]] (NZ) made his T20I debut.\n*''[[Mustafizur Rahman]] became the second bowler for Bangladesh and 16th player overall to take a [[List of five-wicket hauls in Twenty20 International cricket|five-wicket haul in a T20I match]].<ref name=\"Rahman\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/990755.html|title=Most batsmen bowled in a T20I|access-date=26 March 2016|work=ESPN Cricinfo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329000318/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/990755.html|archive-date=29 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''Bangladesh's total is their lowest total in a T20I match.<ref name=\"Ban70\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/990493.html|title=NZ read conditions and rout Bangladesh|access-date=26 March 2016|work=ESPN Cricinfo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329000303/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/990493.html|archive-date=29 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''Ten dismissals in this match were [[bowled]], the most in a T20I match.<ref name=\"10bowled\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/35903938|title=World Twenty20: New Zealand beat Bangladesh for fourth win|access-date=26 March 2016|work=BBC Sport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326150304/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/35903938|archive-date=26 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n----\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = {{anchor|match35}} 3 April\n| time = 19:00\n| daynight = Yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| team2 = {{cr|WIN}}\n| score1 = 155/9 (20 overs)\n| score2 = 161/6 (19.4 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Joe Root]] 54 (36)\n| wickets1 = [[Carlos Brathwaite]] 3/23 (4 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Marlon Samuels]] 85[[not out|*]] (66)\n| wickets2 = [[David Willey (cricketer)|David Willey]] 3/20 (4 overs)\n| toss = West Indies won the toss and elected to field.\n| motm = [[Marlon Samuels]] (WI)\n| umpires = [[Kumar Dharmasena]] (SL) and [[Rod Tucker]] (Aus)\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/951373.html Scorecard]\n| result = {{cr|West Indies}} won by 4 wickets\n| notes = [[Marlon Samuels]] (WI) scored the highest total in a World T20 final.<ref name=\"Samuels85\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/994909.html|title=Last-over heroics, and Samuels' finale|access-date=4 April 2016|work=ESPN Cricinfo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404072454/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2016/content/story/994909.html|archive-date=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''West Indies became the first team to win both the men's and [[2016 ICC Womens World Twenty20 Final|women's World Twenty20s]] on the same day, with the women defeating Australia by 8 wickets.\n}}\n\n[[File:Eden Gardens under floodlights during a match.jpg|wide|center|frame|Eden Gardens under floodlights during [[2016 ICC World Twenty20 Final]].]]\n\n=== 1978 ICC Women's Cricket World Cup ===\n----\n{{Limited overs international\n | date = 1 January 1978\n | team1 = {{crw-rt|IND}}\n | score1 = 63 (39.3 overs)\n | score2 = 65/1 (30.2 overs)\n | team2 = {{crw|ENG}}\n | runs1 = \n | wickets1 = \n | runs2 = \n | wickets2 = \n | result = {{crw|ENG}} won by 9 wickets\n | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/WWC78/ENG-WOMEN_IND-WOMEN_WWC78_WODI2_01JAN1978.html (scorecard)]\n | umpires =\n | motm = \n}}\n\n=== 1997 ICC Women's Cricket World Cup ===\n----\n{{Limited Overs Matches\n | date = 29 December 1997\n | team1 = {{crw-rt|NZL}}\n | score1 = 164 (49.3 overs)\n | score2 = 165/5 (47.4 overs)\n | team2 = {{crw|AUS}}\n | runs1 = \n | wickets1 = \n | runs2 = \n | wickets2 =\n | result =  {{crw|AUS}} won by 5 wickets\n | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/66905.html Scorecard]\n | umpires =\n | motm =\n | toss = \n | rain = \n}}\n\n=== 2016 ICC Women's World Twenty20 ===\n----\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 3 April\n| time = 14:30\n| daynight = \n| team1 = {{crw-rt|AUS}}\n| team2 = {{crw|WIN}}\n| score1 = 148/5 (20 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Elyse Villani]] 52 (37)\n| wickets1 = [[Deandra Dottin]] 2/33 (4 overs)\n| score2 = 149/2 (19.3 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Hayley Matthews]] 66 (45)\n| wickets2 = [[Kristen Beams]] 1/27 (4 overs)\n| result = {{crw|West Indies}} won by 8 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/951419.html Scorecard]\n| umpires = [[Aleem Dar]] (Pak) and [[Richard Illingworth]] (Eng)\n| motm = [[Hayley Matthews]] (WI)\n| toss = Australia won the toss and elected to bat.\n| round =\n| rain = \n| notes = \n}}\n\n----\n===First Day/Night test===\n{{main|Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320}}\n{{Two-innings cricket match\n| date = 22\u201326 November 2019\n| daynight = Yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n\n| score-team1-inns1 = 106 (30.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Shadman Islam]] 29 (52)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Ishant Sharma]] 5/22 (12 overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns1 = 347/9[[Declaration and forfeiture#Declaration|d]] (89.4 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Virat Kohli]] 136 (194)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Al-Amin Hossain]] 3/85 (22.4 overs)\n\n| score-team1-inns2 = 195 (41.1 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] 74 (96)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Umesh Yadav]] 5/53 (14.1 overs)\n\n| score-team2-inns2 = \n| runs-team2-inns2 = \n| wickets-team2-inns2 = \n\n| result = India won by an innings and 46 runs\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1187017.html Scorecard]\n| umpires = [[Marais Erasmus]] (SA) and [[Joel Wilson (umpire)|Joel Wilson]] (WI)\n| motm = [[Ishant Sharma]] (Ind)\n| toss = Bangladesh won the toss and elected to bat.\n| rain = \n| notes =\n}}\n\n==Notable events==\n[[File:Day night test at Eden gardens.jpeg|thumb|330px|Day 1, India's first ever Day/night test match, held at Eden Garden]] \n[[File:Eden gardens manual scoreboard.jpg|thumb|Eden Gardens Manual Scoreboard]]\n[[File:Eden Gardens Block Map.jpg|thumb|Eden Gardens Block Map]]\n* In 1946, an in-form [[Mushtaq Ali]] was dropped from the Indian team selected to play an unofficial test against [[Australian Services XI]]. Following crowd protests (with slogans like \"No Mushtaq, No Test\"), the selectors brought him back to play.<ref name=Mushtaq_Ali>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2001/dec/17mush.htm |title=Unfortunately, they don't look for talent today: The Rediff Interview with Mushtaq Ali |publisher=Rediff.com |date=17 December 2001 |accessdate=12 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201100352/http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2001/dec/17mush.htm |archive-date=1 December 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Rioting occurred at the ground during the 1966/67 West Indies and 1969/70 Australian tours.<ref name=\"cric\" />\n* In 1977, [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] played a Football match against [[Mohun Bagan]] at the stadium. [[Pel\u00e9]] played in that match for the Cosmos. The match was drawn at 2\u20132.\n* 16 football fans died in a stampede after a derby league game between East Bengal and Mohun Bagan on 16 August 1980.\n* Hosted [[Nehru Cup]] in [[1984 Nehru Cup|1984]], where [[India national football team]] played against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Poland national football team|Poland]], [[China national football team|China PR]], [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania U-21]] and [[Vasas Budapest]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Nehru Cup 1984 - Match Details |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nehru84det.html |website=www.rsssf.com |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=16 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116143112/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesn/nehru84det.html |archive-date=16 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Eden Gardens hosted the [[1987 Cricket World Cup Final]] which was first ever [[Cricket World Cup]] final hosted outside England. The match ended with Australia defeating England by 7 runs. This was first time Australia won the [[List of Cricket World Cup finals|Cricket World Cup Final]].\n* The 1996 World Cup semi-final was called off and Sri Lanka awarded the match after crowd disturbances following an Indian batting collapse.<ref name=\"cric\" />\n* During the 2nd final of the [[1997 Pepsi Independence Cup]], the Test and ODI captains of the Indian cricket team of all time (with a few notable exceptions) were given a lap of honour around the stadium.\n* In 1999, leading Indian batsman [[Sachin Tendulkar]] was [[run out]] after colliding with Pakistan's [[Shoaib Akhtar]]. Akhtar had impeded Tendulkar and the crowd rioted, forcing the police to evict the spectators. The match continued in front of an empty stadium.\n* [[Kapil Dev]] took an ODI hat-trick against the Sri Lankans in 1991 at the ground.\n* [[Harbhajan Singh]] took a hat-trick against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in 2000/01 at the ground. He became the first Indian to take a hat-trick in Test cricket.\n*In 2000/01, [[V.V.S. Laxman]] scored 281 against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] in the [[Second Test, 2000\u201301 Border\u2013Gavaskar Trophy]]. This remains the highest score at the ground. He was involved in a memorable 376 runs partnership with [[Rahul Dravid]] who scored 180. They batted through the whole Day 4 of the test match without losing their wickets. Australia were defeated despite enforcing India to follow-on. It was only the third time in Test history that a team had won after being forced to [[follow on]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63920.html |title=Border-Gavaskar Trophy \u2013 2nd Test |publisher=Cricinfo |access-date=19 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623123925/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63920.html |archive-date=23 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is widely considered to be one of the greatest Test matches in cricket history.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1224298.stm | work=BBC News | title=The greatest Test ever? | date=16 March 2001 | access-date=6 October 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117005702/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/sports_talk/1224298.stm | archive-date=17 November 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*In 2005, in an ODI against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], Eden Gardens crowd booed the [[India national cricket team|Indian team]] and [[Greg Chappell]] because of [[Sourav Ganguly]]'s dropping from the team. Chappell allegedly showed middle finger to the crowd. \n*In 2005,Sachin Tendulkar scored his 10,000th run in Test Cricket against Pakistan on this ground making him the second Indian batsman and fifth overall to achieve this feat.\n* Eden Gardens hosted the historic 199th (penultimate) Test match of [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s career against West Indies from 6-10 Nov 2013. India defeated West Indies by an innings and 51 runs in 3 days.\n* On its 150th anniversary, on 13 November 2014, Eden Gardens witnessed the highest ever score by a batsman in One Day Internationals, a 264 off 173 balls scored by [[Rohit Sharma]] during the 4th One Day International of Sri Lanka vs India at the venue.\n*On 3 April 2016, in this venue, within a span of hours, the finals of the ICC world cup Twenty20 tournaments for the [[2016 ICC Women's World Twenty20 Final|women]] and for the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20 Final|men]] were won by the respective [[West Indies women's cricket team|women's]] and [[West Indies cricket team|men's]] teams of the West Indies.\n*The stadium hosted the 200th and 250th home tests for India in 2005 and 2016 respectively.\n* On January 22, 2017, [[Ravindra Jadeja]] became the first Indian left arm spinner to take 150 One Day International wickets, when he dismissed [[Sam Billings]].\n*On September 21, 2017, [[Kuldeep Yadav]] became the third bowler for India to take a hat-trick in an ODI after [[Chetan Sharma]] and [[Kapil Dev]]. When he took a hat-trick against Australia.\n*On November 22, 2019, India's first ever [[Day/night cricket|Day/Night test match]] [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320#2nd Test|between India and Bangladesh]] was hosted at Eden Gardens.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1498140 |title=Bangladesh brace for another historic first against India |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stats and Records==\n===Matches Hosted===\n({{small| as on 5 November 2019}})\n* [[Test cricket|Test]] \u2014 41\n* [[One Day International|ODI]] \u2014 30\n* [[Twenty20 International|T20I]] \u2014 7\n\n===Records===\n* The most runs in Test Matches played here are scored by [[V.V.S. Laxman]] (1217 runs),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/|title=Live cricket scores, commentary, match coverage - Cricket news, statistics - ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=11 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113014130/http://www.espncricinfo.com/|archive-date=13 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> followed by [[Rahul Dravid]] (962 runs) and [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (872 runs). The most wickets taken here was by [[Harbhajan Singh]] (46 wickets) followed by [[Anil Kumble]] (40 wickets) and [[Bishen Singh Bedi]] (29 wickets).\n* The most runs in ODIs scored here by a batsman is by [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (496 runs), followed by [[Mohammed Azharuddin]] (332 runs) and [[Virat Kohli]] (326 runs). The most wickets taken here is by [[Anil Kumble]] and [[Kapil Dev]] (14 wickets each), followed by [[Ravindra Jadeja]] (9 wickets).\n* [[VVS Laxman]] and [[Mohammed Azharuddin]] have scored 5 centuries each at this venue.\n* The highest ever ODI individual score of 264 is made by [[Rohit Sharma]] on this ground against Sri Lanka in 2014.\n*On September 21, 2017, [[Kuldeep Yadav]] became the third bowler for India to take a hat-trick in an ODI after [[Chetan Sharma]] and [[Kapil Dev]]. When he took a hat trick  against Australia.\n*The highest runs scored ever in IPL at Eden Gardens was scored on 28 April 2019. The score was scored by Kolkata Knight Riders against Mumbai Indians. The score was 232/2. MI Scored 198/7 After Hardik Pandya Scored 91(34) Deliveries handing KKR its 100th T20 win.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" !colspan=4|Eden Gardens Records\n|-\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Category !! style=\"width:400px;\"|Test Matches !! style=\"width:400px;\"|ODI Matches !! style=\"width:400px;\"|T20I Matches\n|-\n! scope=row| Highest Inning Score\n|| '''657/d'''  - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|AUS}} (2001)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=1;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103947/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=1;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''404/5''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|SRI}} (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=team;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens ODI Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223104017/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=team;view=innings|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''201/5'''  - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=3;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225040530/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/57980.html?class=3;filter=advanced;orderby=team_score;template=results;type=aggregate;view=innings|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| Lowest Inning Score\n|| '''90''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|WIN}} (1983)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103135/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''120/8''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|SRI}} (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|title=Statistics / Statsguru / ODI matches / Team records / Eden Gardens / Team score|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103501/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=2;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings;wicketsmin1=10;wicketsval1=wickets|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''70''' - {{cr|BAN}} vs {{cr|NZL}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i large victory\"/>\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Innings\n|| '''Innings & 336 runs'''  - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1983)<ref name=\"test large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens Test Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035855/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || {{n/a}} || {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Runs\n|| '''329 runs'''  - {{cr|SA}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1996)<ref name=\"test large victory\" /> \n|| '''161 runs''' - {{cr|ZIM}} vs {{cr|KEN}} (2011)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035536/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''75 runs''' - {{cr|NZ}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035637/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Wickets\n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|AUS}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1969)<ref name=\"test large victory\" /> \n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|SA}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2005)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''6 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2011) and {{cr|SRI}} vs {{cr|AFG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Balls Remaining\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''90 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|KEN}} (1998)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''13 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|PAK}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Runs'''\n|| '''28 runs'''  - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (1972)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035544/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''2 runs''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|RSA}} (1993)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035902/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''55 runs''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225040628/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Wickets''' \n|| '''7 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2012)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 Wickets''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1987)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''4 Wickets''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Balls Remaining'''\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''1 ball''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|WIN}} (1989)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 ball''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of international cricket centuries at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Kolkata/Maidan}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110207010720/http://worldcup2011schedule.com/eden-gardens-cricket-stadium-kolkata-india/  Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Kolkata, India] \u2013 Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Seating Layout\n* [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/14/949.html CricketArchive statistics for Eden gardens]\n* [http://www.kolkatabengalinfo.com/2012/01/kkr-ipl-5-eden-gardens-kolkata-matches.html  IPL-5 Matches at Eden Gardens] \u2013 IPL 2012 Matches at Eden Gardens\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[Cricket World Cup]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Lord's]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[1992 Cricket World Cup]] -->\n | years = [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[ICC World Twenty20]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[2020 ICC World Twenty20]] -->\n | years = [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n\n{{Test cricket grounds in India}}\n{{Kolkata topics}}\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n{{Football stadiums in India}}\n}}\n[[Category:Test cricket grounds in India]]\n[[Category:National stadiums|India]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1864]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Cricket grounds in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Football venues in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1987 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:1996 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:2011 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cricket ground in Kolkata, India}}\n{{distinguish|Eden Garden|Garden of Eden}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| name = Eden Gardens\n| image = File:Eden_Gardens_under_floodlights_during_a_match.jpg\n| country = India\n| location = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|22|33|52|N|88|20|36|E|region:IN_type:landmark|display=it}}\n| seating_capacity = 40,000 (1864\u20131987)<br>100,000+ (1987\u20132011)<br>66,349 (2011\u2013present)\n| owner = [[Indian Army]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/sports/softspot/historic-eden-garden-is-meant-for-bcci-cab-chief_4792.html|title=Historic Eden Garden is meant for BCCI: CAB chief|date=24 August 2007|work=india.com|accessdate=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011033147/http://zeenews.india.com/sports/softspot/historic-eden-garden-is-meant-for-bcci-cab-chief_4792.html|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| operator = [[Cricket Association of Bengal]]\n| embedded = \n{{Infobox cricket ground\n| ground_name = Eden Gardens\n| location = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]]\n| establishment = {{start date and age|1864}}\n| seating_capacity = 66,000\n| floodlights = Yes\n| home club = [[Bengal cricket team|Bengal]]\n| end1 = High Court End [[Image:EdenGardensCricketGroundPitchDimensions.svg|250px]]\n| end2 = Pavilion End\n| tenants = {{ubl|[[India national cricket team]]|[[Bengal cricket team]]|[[Kolkata Knight Riders]]}}\n| international = true\n| firsttestdate = 5\u20138 January\n| firsttestyear = 1934\n| firsttesthome = India\n| firsttestaway = England\n| lasttestdate = 22\u201324 November\n| lasttestyear = 2019\n| lasttesthome = India\n| lasttestaway = Bangladesh\n| firstodidate = 18 February\n| firstodiyear = 1987\n| firstodihome = India\n| firstodiaway = Pakistan\n| lastodidate = 21 September\n| lastodiyear = 2017\n| lastodihome = India\n| lastodiaway = Australia \n| firstt20idate = 29 October\n| firstt20iyear = 2011\n| firstt20ihome = India\n| firstt20iaway = England\n| lastt20idate = 4 November \n| lastt20iyear = 2018\n| lastt20ihome = India \n| lastt20iaway = West Indies\n| firstwodidate = 1 January\n| firstwodiyear = 1978\n| firstwodihome = India\n| firstwodiaway = England\n| lastwodidate  = 9 December\n| lastwodiyear  = 2005\n| lastwodihome  = India\n| lastwodiaway  = England\n| onlywt20idate = 3 April\n| onlywt20iyear = 2016\n| onlywt20ihome = Australia\n| onlywt20iaway = West Indies\n| date = 24 November\n| year = 2019\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57980.html ESPNcricinfo\n| year1 = 1908\u2013present\n| club1 = [[Bengal cricket team]]\n| year2 = 2008\u2013present\n| club2 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n| year3 = 1889-1984\n| club3 = [[Mohun Bagan]]\n| year4 = 1920-1984\n| club4 = [[East Bengal F.C.|East Bengal]]\n| club5 = [[Mohammedan S.C. (Kolkata)|Mohammedan S.C.]]\n| year5 = 1891-1984}}}}\n{{Location map | India Kolkata\n| width   = 200\n| lat_deg = 22.5644\n| lon_deg = 88.3434\n| label   = Eden Gardens\n}}\n\nThe '''Eden Gardens'''  is a [[cricket ground]] in [[Kolkata]], [[India]]. It was established in 1864. It is the oldest cricket stadium in India. It is the second largest cricket stadium in India after the newly built [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], and third in the world after [[Sardar Patel Stadium]] and [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]. It is the home venue of the [[Bengal cricket team]] and the [[Indian Premier League|IPL]] franchise cricket team [[Kolkata Knight Riders]], and is also a venue for [[Test cricket|Test]], [[One Day International|ODI]] and [[Twenty20 International|T20I]] matches of the [[India national cricket team]]. The stadium currently has a capacity of 66,349.<ref>https://www.jagranjosh.com/general-knowledge/top-10-biggest-cricket-stadiums-in-the-world-1509542354-1</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Eden Gardens {{!}} India {{!}} Cricket Grounds {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57980.html |website=Cricinfo |accessdate=19 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708034244/http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57980.html |archive-date=8 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 22 November 2019, the venue hosted the first ever [[Day/night cricket|day/night]] test match in India during [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320#2nd Test|second Test between India and Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27955754/bangladesh-agree-play-day-night-test-eden-gardens |title=Bangladesh agree to play day-night Test at Eden Gardens |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=29 October 2019|date=29 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\nEden Gardens is often regarded as home of Indian cricket. The ground has been referred to as \"cricket's answer to the [[Colosseum]],\" and is widely acknowledged to be one of the most iconic cricket stadiums in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/national-sport/84817197/Cricketing-Colosseum-abuzz-as-New-Zealand-arrive-in-search-of-series-levelling-win|title=Colosseum and Eden Gardens|access-date=14 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718120008/http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/sport/national-sport/84817197/Cricketing-Colosseum-abuzz-as-New-Zealand-arrive-in-search-of-series-levelling-win|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Eden Gardens is called the \u201cMecca of Indian cricket\u201d because it was the first officially built ground for the game of cricket in India.<ref>https://www.inuth.com/sports/cricket/eden-gardens-aka-the-mecca-of-indian-cricket-gets-wall-art-of-almost-four-storeys-see-photos/</ref> Eden Gardens has hosted matches in major international competitions including the [[Cricket World Cup|World Cup]], [[World Twenty20]] and [[Asia Cup]]. In 1987, Eden Gardens became the second stadium to host a [[1987 Cricket World Cup Final|World Cup final]]. The [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]] final was held at the Eden Gardens where the West Indies beat [[England]] in a very closely fought encounter.\n\n==Stadium History==\nThe stadium was established in 1864. The stadium gets its name from the Eden Gardens, one of the oldest parks in Kolkata, adjacent to the stadium, designed in 1841 and named after the Eden sisters of [[George Eden, 1st Earl of Auckland|Lord Auckland]], the then [[Governor-General of India]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bag|first1=Shamik|title=In the shadow of Eden|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/travel/content/current/story/495627.html|website=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=19 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619204248/http://www.espncricinfo.com/travel/content/current/story/495627.html|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=live|date=January 2000}}</ref> Initially it was named 'Auckland Circus Gardens' but later changed to 'Eden Gardens' by its makers inspired by [[Garden of Eden]] in the Bible.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eden Gardens|url=http://kolkatacitytours.com/eden-gardens-stadium-kolkata/|publisher=Kolkata City Tours|accessdate=11 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426154752/http://kolkatacitytours.com/eden-gardens-stadium-kolkata/|archive-date=26 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> According to popular culture, Babu Rajchandra Das, the then zamindar(landlord) of Kolkata, had gifted one of his biggest gardens besides river [[Hooghly River|Hooghly]], to Viceroy Lord Auckland Eden and his sister Emily Eden after they helped him by saving his 3rd daughter from a fatal disease. From then onwards the garden's name was changed from Mar Bagan to Eden Gardens. The cricket grounds were built between [[Babughat]] and [[Fort William, India|Fort William]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketassociationofbengal.com/history.php|title=Early History of Bengal Cricket leading to the formation of the Cricket Association of Bengal in 1928|website=CAB|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102855/http://www.cricketassociationofbengal.com/history.php|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The stadium is in the [[B. B. D. Bagh]] area of the city, near the State Secretariat and opposite to the [[Calcutta High Court]].\n\nThe first recorded Test at the venue was held in 1934 between [[England national cricket team|England]] and [[Indian national cricket team|India]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/151798.html|title=Wisden Almanack Test Report|website=[[ESPN Cricinfo]]|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103602/http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/151798.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> its first One Day International in 1987 between India and [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/150679.html|title=Wisden Almanack ODI Match Report|website=[[ESPN Cricinfo]]|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103933/http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/150679.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and its first T20 international in 2011 between India and England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/582163.html|title=Eden Gardens T20I Results|website=[[ESPN Cricinfo]]|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=14 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223160533/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/582163.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Hero Cup]] semi final featuring India and [[South African national cricket team|South Africa]] was the first [[Day/night cricket|Day/Night match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151069.html|title=Hero Cup 1993-94|website=[[ESPN Cricinfo]]|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103528/http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151069.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Eden Gardens Kolkata.jpg|750px|Panoramic View of the Eden Gardens Stadium during [[IPL 2008]]. Note that it was pre-renovation and had benches rather than individual seats. In this configuration, the stadium could seat over 94,000 fans on game day}}\n\n== Stadium ==\n[[File:Eden Gardens front.jpg|thumb|right|Eden Gardens front facade]]\nThe Stadium is the headquarters of the [[Cricket Association of Bengal]]. Apart from International matches, the stadium hosts matches for domestic Indian cricket and is the home venue for [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]. The stadium's Club House is named after former [[Chief Minister of West Bengal]] [[Bidhan Chandra Roy|Dr. B. C. Roy]]. \n\n=== 1987 Renovation ===\nBefore the 1987 World Cup, the stadium had a capacity of 40,000. It was expanded to 94,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hcp.co.in/project/eden-gardens-stadium|title=Eden Gardens Stadium, Kolkata 1986 -1987|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223160441/https://www.hcp.co.in/project/eden-gardens-stadium|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Renovations included changes to press box, club house and television infrastructure. 42 columns provided the support for large roofs and multi-tiered covered stands. Even after the renovation, not all seats were covered and many sections lacked individual seats.\n\nHowever, match day attendance of more than 100,000 spectators<ref name=\"cric\">{{cite web|url=http://content.cricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57980.html|title=Eden Gardens|publisher=CricInfo|accessdate=12 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090509201052/http://content.cricinfo.com/india/content/ground/57980.html|archive-date=9 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> have been recorded on at least 6 occasions until the early 2000s.\n\n===2011 Renovation===\n[[File:Eden Gardens.jpg|thumb|right|The ground before [[Cricket World Cup 2011]] renovation.]]\n[[File:Eden Gardens after renovations.jpg|thumb|Eden Gardens after renovations.]]\n\nEden Gardens underwent renovation for the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>[http://www.worldinteriordesignnetwork.com/news/kolkatas_eden_gardens_stadium_gets_a_new_look_for_cricket_world_cup_2011_090616 Kolkata's Eden Gardens stadium gets a new look for Cricket World Cup 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616165005/http://www.worldinteriordesignnetwork.com/news/kolkatas_eden_gardens_stadium_gets_a_new_look_for_cricket_world_cup_2011_090616/ |date=16 June 2010 }}. World Interior Design Network. Retrieved on 10 June 2010</ref> Renovation had been undertaken to meet the standards set by the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) for the 2011 World Cup. The [[Cricket Association of Bengal]] retained the team of Burt Hill and VMS to renovate the Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium. The plans for the renovated stadium included a new clubhouse and players' facilities, upgrades of the exterior walls to give the stadium a new look, cladding the existing roof structure with a new metal skin, new/upgraded patron amenities & signage and general infrastructure improvements. The upgrade also meant reduction of the seating capacity to about 68,000 from around 94,000 before the upgrade.\n\nDue to unsafe conditions arising from the incomplete renovations, the ICC withdrew the India vs. England match from the Eden Gardens. This match, scheduled on 27 February 2011,<ref name=\"India News\">{{cite web |url=http://news.indiavoice.info/cricket/eden-gardens-loses-world-cup-match-2011012808510/ |title=Eden Gardens loses World Cup match |publisher=IndiaVoice |date=28 January 2011 |accessdate=30 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316162859/http://news.indiavoice.info/cricket/eden-gardens-loses-world-cup-match-2011012808510/ |archive-date=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> was played in [[Bengaluru]] at [[M.Chinnaswamy Stadium]].\n\nThe stadium hosted the remaining three scheduled World Cup 2011 Matches on 15, 18 and 20 March 2011. In the last of these three matches (Kenya vs Zimbabwe), the stadium had the minimal ticket-purchasing crowd in its recorded history with 15 spectators having bought tickets.<ref name=Roar>{{cite news |last=Basu |first=Rith |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110322/jsp/calcutta/story_13747391.jsp |title=Empty end to Eden's Cup \u2013 And the roar died: just 15 match-day tickets sold for Zimbabwe-Kenya tie |publisher=[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)]] |date=22 March 2011 |accessdate=12 October 2011 |location=Calcutta, India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110410041411/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110322/jsp/calcutta/story_13747391.jsp |archive-date=10 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Stands===\nEden Gardens stands have been named after prominent local cricketers and soldiers. On January 22, 2017, 2 stands were named after Indian cricketers - [[Sourav Ganguly]] and [[Pankaj Roy]] while 2 more were after cricket administrators - BN Dutt ([[Presidents of the Board of Control for Cricket in India|BCCI President]] 1988-1990) and [[Jagmohan Dalmiya]] (BCCI President 2001\u201304, 2013 - interim, 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2017/jan/23/eden-gardens-stands-named-after-ganguly-and-dalmiya-1562505.html|title=Eden Gardens stands named after Ganguly and Dalmiya|website=The New Indian Express|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102503/http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/cricket/2017/jan/23/eden-gardens-stands-named-after-ganguly-and-dalmiya-1562505.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Dalmiya served as [[List of International Cricket Council presidents|ICC President]] from 1997 to 2000.\n\nOn 27 April 2017, 4 stands were named after Indian soldiers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/ipl-2017/ipl-2017-eden-gardens-stands-immortalise-indian-army-bravehearts/story-odGrHuBlhA93tW0N91KQfL.html|title=Eden Garden now has a stand in memory of Indian Army bravehearts|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=28 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222124615/http://www.hindustantimes.com/ipl-2017/ipl-2017-eden-gardens-stands-immortalise-indian-army-bravehearts/story-odGrHuBlhA93tW0N91KQfL.html|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> - Colonel [[Neelakantan Jayachandran Nair]], Havildar [[Hangpan Dada]], Lieutenant Colonel [[Dhan Singh Thapa]] and Subedar [[Joginder Singh (soldier)|Joginder Singh Sahnan]]. LC Thapa and Subedar Singh are [[Param Vir Chakra]] awardees - the highest wartime military decoration in India while Col Nair and Havildar Dada are [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashok Chakra]] - the highest peacetime military decoration.\n\n==Experience==\n\n[[File:Eden Gardens during IPL 2017.jpg|thumb|Massive crowd during [[Kolkata Knight Riders|KKR]] Vs [[Royal Challengers Bangalore|RCB]] [[2017 Indian Premier League|2017 IPL]] match.]] \n[[File:Eden_Garden_Stadium_at_Night_03.jpg|thumb|Night View of Eden Gardens]]\nEden Gardens is renowned for its large and vociferous crowds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisdenindia.com/cricket-blog/time-to-get-the-eden-roar-going-across-india/213111|last1=Premachandran|first1=Dileep|website=Wisden India|title=Time to get the Eden roar going across India|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102924/http://www.wisdenindia.com/cricket-blog/time-to-get-the-eden-roar-going-across-india/213111|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"sportskeeda\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/eden-gardens-heritage-plot-of-records-romance|title=Eden Gardens: A heritage plot of records and romance|last1=Saeed|first1=Umaima|website=Sports Keeda|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223103117/https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/eden-gardens-heritage-plot-of-records-romance|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live|date=4 July 2016}}</ref> Former [[Australian national cricket team|Aussie captain]] [[Steve Waugh]] considers the Eden Gardens as '[[Lord's]] of the subcontinent'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eden Gardens is the 'Lord's' of sub-continent: Steve Waugh|url=http://www.cricketcountry.com/news/eden-gardens-is-the-lords-of-sub-continent-steve-waugh-200714|website=Cricket Country|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223160540/http://www.cricketcountry.com/news/eden-gardens-is-the-lords-of-sub-continent-steve-waugh-200714|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Dileep Vengsarkar]] called Eden Gardens as the second best after Lords.<ref name=\"sportskeeda\" /> Former Indian Captain and Kolkata Native [[Sourav Ganguly]] confessed once in an interview that the roar of crowd at the stadium he heard when India defeated Australia in the [[Second Test, 2000\u201301 Border\u2013Gavaskar Trophy|Second Test of 2000\u201301 Border\u2013Gavaskar Trophy]] was the loudest he had ever heard.\n[[File:Bell at eden gardens.jpg|thumb|right|The Bell at the Eden Gardens]]\nIn 2016, a bell was added to the stadium to ring in the start of day's play for test cricket and start of match for ODI & T20I matches. [[Kapil Dev]] was the first person to ring the bell to start the test match between India and [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/india-vs-new-zealand-kapil-dev-inaugurates-bell-ringing-ritual-at-eden-gardens-3027820.html|title=India vs New Zealand: Kapil Dev inaugurates bell ringing ritual at Eden Gardens|website=Firstpost|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223110529/http://www.firstpost.com/sports/india-vs-new-zealand-kapil-dev-inaugurates-bell-ringing-ritual-at-eden-gardens-3027820.html|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket World Cup matches==\nEden Gardens has hosted 15 '''Cricket World Cup''' matches hosted in India across formats and men's and women's cricket. Eden Gardens has hosted 6 [[Cricket World Cup]] matches in [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]] (2), [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]] (1), [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011]] (3). The stadium hosted 5 T20I  matches during [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]]. The stadium hosted 2 [[Women's Cricket World Cup]] matches - one each in [[1978 Women's Cricket World Cup|1978]] and [[1997 Women's Cricket World Cup|1997]] and one Women T20I match during the [[2016 ICC Women's World Twenty20]] tournament.\n\nDue to Eden Garden's iconic status, it has hosted 4 finals (1987 ODI CWC, 2016 T20I, 1997 Women's CWC and 2016 Women's T20I) and 1 semifinal (1996 ODI CWC).\n\n=== 1987 ICC Cricket World Cup ===\n {{Limited overs matches\n | date =23 October 1987\n | team1 ={{cr-rt|ZIM}}\n | runs1 = [[Kevin Arnott (cricketer)|Kevin Arnott]] 51 (83)\n | score1 = 228/5 (50 overs)\n | wickets1 = [[Stephen Boock]] 2/43 (10 overs)\n | score2 = 229/6 (47.4 overs)\n | runs2 = [[Jeff Crowe]] 88[[not out|*]] (105)\n | wickets2 = [[Ali Shah]] 2/34 (10 overs)\n | team2 ={{cr|NZL}}\n | result ={{cr|NZL}} won by 4 wickets\n | motm = [[Jeff Crowe]] (NZ)\n | report = [http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/65106.html Scorecard]\n}}\n----\n{{main|1987 Cricket World Cup Final}}\n\n {{Limited overs matches\n | date =8 November 1987\n | team1 ={{cr-rt|AUS}}\n | score1 = 253/5 (50 overs)\n | runs1 = [[David Boon]] 75 (125)\n | wickets1 = [[Eddie Hemmings (cricketer)|Eddie Hemmings]] 2/48 (10 overs)\n | score2 = 246/8 (50 overs)\n | runs2 = [[Bill Athey]] 58 (103)\n | wickets2 = [[Allan Border]] 2/38 (7 overs)\n | team2 ={{cr|ENG}}\n | motm = [[David Boon]] (Aus)\n | result ={{crw|AUS}} won by 7 runs\n | report =[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/65117.html Scorecard]\n}}\n----\n\n=== 1996 ICC Cricket World Cup ===\n\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 13 March 1996\n|