ins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035536/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/largest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''75 runs''' - {{cr|NZ}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i large victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035637/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=3;filter=advanced;ground=292;orderby=team_score;orderbyad=reverse;template=results;type=team;view=innings|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Wickets\n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|AUS}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1969)<ref name=\"test large victory\" /> \n|| '''10 Wickets''' - {{cr|SA}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2005)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''6 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2011) and {{cr|SRI}} vs {{cr|AFG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| Largest Victory - By Balls Remaining\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''90 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|KEN}} (1998)<ref name=\"ODI large victory\" /> \n|| '''13 balls''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|PAK}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i large victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Runs'''\n|| '''28 runs'''  - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (1972)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035544/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=1;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''2 runs''' - {{cr|IND}} vs {{cr|RSA}} (1993)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens ODI Record|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225035902/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=2;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|| '''55 runs''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|BAN}} (2016)<ref name=\"T20i narrow victory\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|title=Eden Gardens T20I Records|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225040628/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/team/smallest_margins.html?class=3;id=292;type=ground|archive-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Wickets''' \n|| '''7 Wickets''' - {{cr|ENG}} vs {{cr|IND}} (2012)<ref name=\"test narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 Wickets''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|IND}} (1987)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''4 Wickets''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name = \"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|-\n! scope=row| '''Narrowest Victory - By Balls Remaining'''\n| {{n/a}} \n|| '''1 ball''' - {{cr|PAK}} vs {{cr|WIN}} (1989)<ref name=\"ODI narrow victory\" /> \n|| '''2 ball''' - {{cr|WIN}} vs {{cr|ENG}} (2016)<ref name =\"T20i narrow victory\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of international cricket centuries at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at Eden Gardens]]\n* [[List of stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Kolkata/Maidan}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110207010720/http://worldcup2011schedule.com/eden-gardens-cricket-stadium-kolkata-india/  Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Kolkata, India] \u2013 Eden Gardens Cricket Stadium Seating Layout\n* [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/14/949.html CricketArchive statistics for Eden gardens]\n* [http://www.kolkatabengalinfo.com/2012/01/kkr-ipl-5-eden-gardens-kolkata-matches.html  IPL-5 Matches at Eden Gardens] \u2013 IPL 2012 Matches at Eden Gardens\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[Cricket World Cup]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Lord's]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[1992 Cricket World Cup]] -->\n | years = [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = [[ICC World Twenty20]]<br>Final Venue\n | before = [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla]]\n | after = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]<!-- [[2020 ICC World Twenty20]] -->\n | years = [[2016 ICC World Twenty20|2016]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n\n{{Test cricket grounds in India}}\n{{Kolkata topics}}\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n{{Football stadiums in India}}\n}}\n[[Category:Test cricket grounds in India]]\n[[Category:National stadiums|India]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1864]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Cricket grounds in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Football venues in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1987 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:1996 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:2011 Cricket World Cup stadiums]]\n", "name_user": "Benstark1533", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a point in Notable events section... this was about Sachin Tendulkar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eden_Gardens"}
{"title_page": "Deezer", "text_new": "{{short description|Web-based music streaming service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Deezer\n| logo             = [[File:Deezer logo.svg|250px]]\n| company_type     = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2007|8|df=yes}}<br>[[Paris]], [[France]]\n| location_city    = Paris, [[\u00cele-de-France]]\n| location_country = France<ref name=\"legal\">{{cite web|url= http://www.deezer.com/legal/legal |title= Deezer.com legal |accessdate= 2015-12-06}}</ref>\n| founder          = Daniel Marhely<br>Jonathan Benassaya\n| key_people       = Hans-Holger Albrecht<ref name=press /> ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Laurent Cordonnier ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])<br> Daniel Marhely ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| services         = [[Streaming media|Music streaming]]\n| industry         = Music, podcast, and video\n| owner            = \n| parent           = [[Access Industries]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7502855/deezer-access-industries-french-approval-len-blavatnik |title=Warner Music's Parent Company Now In Control of Deezer Following French Approval |magazine=Billboard |date=9 August 2016 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xAsiHkrR?url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7502855/deezer-access-industries-french-approval-len-blavatnik |archivedate=12 February 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><br><small>(2016\u2013present)</small>\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.deezer.com/}}\n| alexa            = {{Increase}} 1,529 ({{As of|2019|02|28|alt=February 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |title=Deezer.com Traffic, Demographics and Competitors - Alexa |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/deezer.com |website=www.alexa.com |accessdate=28 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| commercial       = Yes\n| registration     = Required\n| num_users        =\n| language         = 180+ countries<ref name=\"press\">{{cite web| url= http://www.deezer.com/company/press | title= Deezer press page show company stats | accessdate= 2015-12-06}}</ref>\n| current_status   = Active\n| native_clients   = [[World Wide Web|Web]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Mobile]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[MacOS]]\n}}\n\n'''Deezer''' is a French online [[music streaming service]]. It allows users to listen to music content from record labels, including [[Universal Music Group]], [[Sony Music]] and [[Warner Music Group]] (owned by Deezer's parent company [[Access Industries]]) on various devices online or offline. Created in [[Paris]], [[France]], Deezer currently has 56 million licensed tracks in its library, with over 30,000 radio channels, 14 million [[monthly active users]], and 7 million paid subscribers as of January 2019.<ref name=\"deezer.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deezer.com/company|title=About us|work=Deezer}}</ref>  The service is available for Web, [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Mobile]], [[BlackBerry OS]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[MacOS]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Deezer.svg|thumb|250px|First logo of Deezer.]]\nIn 2006, Daniel Marhely developed the first version of Deezer, called Blogmusik, in Paris. His idea was to give unlimited access to music lovers through [[streaming media|streaming]] technology.\n\nThe site in its original incarnation was charged with copyright infringement by French agency [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des auteurs, compositeurs et \u00e9diteurs de musique|SACEM]], and after being shut down in April 2007<ref name=\"ina\"/> was relaunched as Deezer in August 2007, having reached an agreement with SACEM to pay copyright holders with revenue from advertising on the site<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/08/21/blogmusik-comes-back-with-a-legal-free-music-on-demand-service/ |title=Exclusive: BlogMusik To Go Legit; Launches Free & Legal Music On Demand |work=TechCrunch |date=21 August 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5G9jSiv?url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/08/21/blogmusik-comes-back-with-a-legal-free-music-on-demand-service/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and by giving users the ability to download songs streamed on Deezer from [[iTunes]], with Deezer receiving a commission from each purchase.<ref name=\"ina\"/>\n\n===Launch===\nAt the time of its launch in 2007, Deezer had not yet negotiated agreements with major music labels and therefore offered a limited catalogue.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  It took more than two years for agreements to be signed with the four largest labels, as well as various smaller ones, but by 2011 the company had rights to about eight million songs.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  During August 2007, its first month of operations, Deezer saw about 773,000 visitors to its site, with traffic increasing rapidly in the next several years\u20142.75 million people used the service in May 2008, and there were seven million users by December 2009.<ref name=\"ina\"/>\n\nDespite the high traffic, Deezer almost immediately ran into financial problems\u2014during the first half of 2008, the company saw revenue of just 875,000 euros, not enough to pay its licensing fees.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  In July 2008, the company began running ads itself through advertising agency Deezer Media; in October, Deezer secured $8.4 million in funding from AGF Private Equity and CM-CIC Capital Prive, bringing total investment in the company to $15.8 million.<ref name=\"wsj oct 2012\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/tech-europe/2012/10/08/deezers-expansion-plans-get-a-boost/ | title=Deezer\u2019s Expansion Plans Get a Boost | newspaper=Wall Street Journal | date=8 October 2012 | accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> The company introduced mandatory registration in February 2009 to gather more precise data on users, in order to run more targeted ads, and in November 2009 began running audio ads between songs.<ref name=\"ina\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inaglobal.fr/en/music/article/deezer-profitability-down-line |title=Deezer: Profitability Down the Line? |publisher=INA Global |date=19 August 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403164334/http://www.inaglobal.fr/en/music/article/deezer-profitability-down-line?tq=4 |archivedate=3 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November 2009, Deezer launched a new three-tier service model.  While continuing basic free web streaming, the company also introduced two subscription services\u2014users paying \u20ac4.99 monthly received higher-quality music without ads, and users paying \u20ac9.99 monthly gained access to downloadable applications for computers, as well as [[Android (operating system)|Android]],  [[BlackBerry]], and [[iOS]] mobile devices.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/11/05/digital-music-startup-deezer-debuts-desktop-client-premium-offering/ |title=Digital music startup Deezer debuts desktop client, premium offering |work=TechCrunch |date=5 November 2009 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5I10EIt?url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/11/05/digital-music-startup-deezer-debuts-desktop-client-premium-offering/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, the company's CEO and co-founder, Jonathan Benassaya, was replaced as CEO by Axel Dauchez, after fewer than 15,000 of Deezer's 12 million users signed up for its subscription services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/28/post-bloodletting-deezer-appoints-a-new-ceo/ |title=Post bloodletting, Deezer appoints a new CEO |work=TechCrunch |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5ItPrqj?url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/28/post-bloodletting-deezer-appoints-a-new-ceo/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>  In August 2010, mobile operator [[Orange S.A.|Orange]] partnered with Deezer in a deal to include free access to Deezer Premium, the highest tier of Deezer's streaming packages, with some of Orange's telecommunications contracts in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendigest.com/news/orange-brings-deezer-premium-to-its-customers/view.html |title=Orange brings Deezer Premium to its customers |publisher=Screen Digest |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5JgHziH?url=http://www.screendigest.com/news/orange-brings-deezer-premium-to-its-customers/view.html |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Almost immediately after the partnership began, the rate of users signing up for Deezer's premium services went from 6,000 a month to 100,000; by January 2011, 500,000 people were subscribing to the service, with the million-subscriber mark reached in the middle of 2011, half a year ahead of schedule.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  The two companies expanded their partnership in September 2011 to include Orange contract customers in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/66bdfd5c-d939-11e0-bd7e-00144feabdc0.html |title=Deezer takes on Spotify with Orange deal |newspaper=Financial Times |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5JROpX1?url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/66bdfd5c-d939-11e0-bd7e-00144feabdc0.html |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Also in September, Deezer added [[Facebook]] integration to its service, allowing users to send music to one another via that social media service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/deezer-enters-realm-of-facebook--828792 |title=Deezer enters realm of Facebook |publisher=Telecompaper |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5K0dI3g?url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/deezer-enters-realm-of-facebook--828792 |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Expansion to more countries===\n[[File:Availability of Deezer in the World.svg|thumb|350px|Availability of Deezer in the world {{as of|2016|8|lc=on}}.]]\nDeezer was launched in France in 2007, where it was the market leader as of 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sophie Sassard |title=Deezer: The French music streaming service taking on Spotify, Apple and Amazon |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/deezer-music-streaming-spotify-amazon-apple-subscritpiton-hans-holger-albrecht-len-blavatnik-a7940896.html |accessdate=27 December 2018 |work=The Independent |date=20 September 2017 |quote=The unlisted company, which launched a decade ago, is the market leader in its home market of France}}</ref> On 7 December 2011, Deezer, at the time available only in Belgium, France and the United Kingdom, announced plans to expand worldwide during the rest of 2011 and continuing into 2012.<ref name=\"tech dec 2011\"/> According to the company, it planned to make its services available to the whole of Europe by the end of the year, to the Americas (excluding the United States) by the end of January 2012, to Africa and Southeast Asia by the end of February, and the rest of the world (excluding Japan) by the end of June.<ref name=\"tech dec 2011\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/12/07/deezer-plans-to-launch-in-200-countries-by-june-2012-but-not-in-the-usa/|title=Deezer plans to launch music service in 200 countries by June 2012 (but not in the US and Japan)|work=TechCrunch|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt took until 15 March 2012 for service to be available across the whole of Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/eu/2012/03/15/deezer-now-covers-all-european-countries-from-iceland-to-russia-46-countries/|title=Deezer now covers all European countries from Iceland to Russia (46 countries)|work=The Next Web| date=15 March 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> while service launched in Australia, Canada, and New Zealand on 25 April.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2012/04/25/spotify-rival-deezer-launches-in-canada-australia-and-new-zealand-still-noticeably-absent-from-the-us/| title=Spotify rival Deezer continues its worldwide expansion with the launch in Canada, Australia, and New Zealand|work=The Next Web|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> On 8 June, Deezer announced availability in 35 Latin American countries, though not in Brazil, Cuba, or Venezuela.<ref name=\"tnw lat am\">{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/la/2012/06/07/music-streaming-service-deezer-goes-live-in-35-latin-american-territories-today/|title=Music streaming service Deezer goes live in 35 Latin American territories today|work=The Next Web|date=7 June 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  On 15 August, Deezer announced it would be available in Indonesia, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand within several weeks.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/08/15/european-music-streaming-service-deezer-heads-to-asia-partners-with-telco-dtac-in-thailand/|title=European Music Streaming Service Deezer Heads to Asia; Partners With Telco dTac In Thailand |work=TechCrunch|date=15 August 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2012, Deezer announced that it had received $130 million in funding from [[Access Industries]], to be used for further international expansion.<ref name=\"wsj oct 2012\"/>  Two days later, the company announced that it had expanded into 76 new markets, bringing its worldwide total to 160 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/10/10/3482702/deezer-expansion-160-countries-no-us-plans|title=Deezer's streaming music service now available in 160 countries, US market 'not ready'|work=The Verge|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  On 21 December, Deezer announced a new service level offering two hours of free, ad-supported music streaming a month, available to users worldwide, the company's first free music streaming service outside France.<ref name=\"wsj dec 2012\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324461604578191043343259734|title=Spotify Rival Deezer Eyes U.S|work=Wall Street Journal|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  CEO Dauchez said that Deezer was also looking for a partner to introduce service in the United States, who was \"able to provide us with a significant volume of subscribers\" to help offset what he called the \"unbelievably high\" costs of entering the US market.<ref name=\"wsj dec 2012\"/>\n\nAs of December 2012, Deezer had about two million users paying for subscriptions, out of a monthly active user base of about seven million, with 20 million songs in its library.<ref name=\"tech interview\"/>  By 2016, according to CEO Dauchez, the company aimed to have five percent of the global music market.<ref name=\"tech interview\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/09/deezer-ceo-streaming-music/|title=Deezer\u2019s CEO Axel Dauchez On Cracking Into The U.S. And Why It\u2019s Not Just Another Spotify|work=TechCrunch|date=9 October 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Deezer announced its expansion into 22 new countries across Africa, Asia, Brazil,  the [[Middle East]], and the [[United States]], bringing its total to 182.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/01/28/deezer-takes-on-spotify-with-expansions-in-middle-east-africa-brazil-and-asia/|title=Deezer Takes On Spotify With Expansions In Middle East, Africa, Brazil And Asia|work=TechCrunch|date=28 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.challenges.fr/high-tech/20131120.CHA7207/deezer-compte-se-lancer-aux-etats-unis-en-2014.html Deezer compte se lancer aux Etats-Unis en 2014], ''Challenges'', 20 November 2013</ref> However, the United States launch has been restricted to a limited number of device promotions.<ref>[http://www.cnet.com/news/deezer-entering-us-will-sound-like-spotify-act-like-netflix/ Deezer, entering US] www.cnet.com. Retrieved on 2016-01-23.</ref> In July 2016, Deezer added the U.S. to the supported country list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deezer Music Preview for Windows 10 PC and Mobile is now available for U.S. users|url=http://m.windowscentral.com/deezer-preview-windows-10-pc-and-mobile-now-available-us-users|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref>  As of February 2018, Deezer listed on its website 189 countries where the service was available.<ref>[http://developers.deezer.com/guidelines/countries Deezer for developers]. Developers.deezer.com. Retrieved on 2018-02-28.</ref>\n\n===After expansion===\nFollowing this expansion, Deezer announced in 2013 partnerships with [[LG Electronics]], [[Samsung Electronics]], and [[Toshiba]] that saw Deezer apps made available on smart TV platforms,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/02/06/deezer-is-to-bring-its-streaming-music-service-to-smart-tvs-via-deals-with-samsung-lg-and-toshiba/ | title=Deezer is bringing its streaming music service to smart TVs, via deals with Samsung, LG and Toshiba | accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> along with a new brand identity developed in association with the illustrator mcbess.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.designweek.co.uk/we-like/mcbess-draws-for-deezer/3035958.article| title=McBess draws for Deezer | accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSince then, Deezer has made a number of announcements, including its Developer Reward Scheme, mobile App Studio, and API upgrades,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2013/03/13/music-streaming-service-deezer-adds-app-discovery-to-smartphones-brings-app-activity-to-its-social-bar/?fromcat=all| title=Music streaming service Deezer adds third-party app discovery to smartphones, updates its API | publisher=The Next Web |accessdate=13 March 2013}}</ref> a new, exclusive beta version of its mobile app for Android users,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/04/03/deezer-for-android-beta/| title=Deezer for Android gets a redesign, predictive search function in new beta version | publisher=Engadget |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> and the new Deezer app for [[Windows 8]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2013/04/17/deezer-launches-a-windows-8-app-for-its-on-demand-streaming-music-service-ahead-of-spotify-and-rdio/?fromcat=all| title=Deezer launches Windows 8 app for its on-demand music streaming service ahead of Spotify and Rdio | publisher=The Next Web |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nApril 2013 also saw Deezer update its iOS app with a new smart caching feature, allowing the app to identify and remember a user's most played tracks, even in areas of poor network coverage.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://musically.com/2013/04/26/deezer-adds-smart-caching-to-its-ios-app/| title=Deezer adds \u2018smart caching\u2019 to its iOS app | publisher=Music Ally |accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Deezer announced a new partnership with [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]] giving [[Samsung Galaxy S5]] users in Europe a free, six months Deezer Premium+ subscription. Samsung and Deezer extended their partnership by offering a six-month, free of charge subscription to Deezer Premium+ for Samsung's Multiroom Wireless Audio Products, including its M5 and M7 line of Multiroom wireless audio speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/items/entertainment/70726-six-months-music-free-samsung-deezer/|title=Six months of music free from Samsung and Deezer|website=HEXUS|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> Samsung UK and Deezer offered this promotion again from 2016-2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samsung.com/uk/offer/deezer/|title=Up to 2 years of music when you buy two or more selected Multiroom products|website=Samsung uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currys.co.uk/gbuk/deezer-1346-commercial.html|title=How to claim your complimentary Deezer Premium+ {{!}} Currys|website=www.currys.co.uk|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Deezer and Google announced that the Google [[Chromecast]] would be supporting Deezer's Android and [[iPhone]] apps to allow users to stream music from their phone to their televisions through the Chromecast. Chromecast support became available to Deezer Premium+ users from 25 June 2014 onwards in Australia, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Finland, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, South Korea, Spain, Sweden,  Switzerland, and the United Kingdom. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn September 2014, Deezer announced Deezer Elite, a new exclusive service made for and in partnership with [[Sonos]]. Deezer Elite provides CD-quality audio to U.S. users of [[Sonos]] Hi-Fi Systems. The service is available worldwide to Sonos users of Deezer only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/exceptional-audio-quality-with-deezer-elite-and-sonos/|title=Exceptional audio quality with Deezer Elite and Sonos|work=deezer.com}}</ref> Deezer Elite \"High-Resolution Audio\" is lossless CD quality (16bit/44.1&nbsp;kHz) and not \"Hi-Res\" or [[high-resolution audio]]. Sonos does not support Hi-Res (24/96, 24/192 or similar) streaming.\n\nDeezer HiFi offers 36 million tracks of 16-Bit/44.1&nbsp;kHz of FLAC quality music for a $19.95 monthly subscription in the United States. It is \"Only available on selected soundsystems and the Desktop App,\u201d and offers downloads to phones at 320 kbit/s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deezer.com/en/offers/hifi|title=Deezer HiFi|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer rolled out a new user interface for its website player. This new change in design was widely welcomed by numerous users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/our-smart-new-look/|title=Our smart new look|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer announced that [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] SoundTouch and SoundLink products would now be supported for Deezer Premium+ service. This partnership will first be rolled out in the United States and then will be available to worldwide users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/u-s-music-fans-can-now-enjoy-deezer-premium-via-bose-products/|title=U.S. music fans can now enjoy Deezer Premium+ on Bose products|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer announced that [[Stitcher Radio]] would be merging into Deezer. By 2015, Deezer users would be able to use Stitcher Radio features within Deezer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stitcher.com/blog/?p=1588|title=Stitcher joins Deezer! \u00ab  Stitcher Blog|work=stitcher.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Deezer and Pepsi announced a partnership to set up the Midem Artist Accelerator to support managers and labels as they grow the profiles of their artists.<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hottopics.ht/stories/consumer/deezer-talks-streaming-music |title= Deezer: bring on the competition, there are 3.47bn more streaming music consumers to go round |publisher=Hot Topics |date=9 January 2015 |first=Tim |last=Green |accessdate=14 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"musically\">{{cite web|url=http://musically.com/2014/12/20/midem-pepsi-deezer-team-artist-accelerator/ |title=Midem, Pepsi, and Deezer team up for 'artist accelerator' |publisher=musically |date=20 December 2014 |accessdate=14 January 2015 }}</ref> In   June 2016, it sold Stitcher to [[E.W. Scripps Company]] for $4.5 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/scripps-buys-stitcher-1201789683/|title=Scripps Buys Podcast Service Stitcher from Deezer|first=Janko|last=Roettgers|date=6 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Deezer integrated [[Triton Digital]] to monetize the free users with programmatic audio ads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ppc.land/deezer-audio-ads-now-available-via-triton-digital/|title=Deezer audio ads now available via Triton Digital|date=2018-12-13|website=PPC Land|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref> Deezer also pushes banner advertisements for WAZE, even for premium subscribers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAt November 7, 2019, Deezer released Spleeter, an open-source \"audio source separation\" utility written in [[Python (programming language)|Python]] that uses the [[TensorFlow]] machine learning library and pretrained models for audio \"stem\" extraction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deezer.io/releasing-spleeter-deezer-r-d-source-separation-engine-2b88985e797e|title=Releasing Spleeter: Deezer R&D source separation engine|last=Moussallam|first=Manuel|date=2019-11-04|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Last.fm  integration==\nIn January 2012, [[Last.fm]] announced that Deezer would integrate with [[Last.fm]], allowing users to send songs from Deezer to their Last.fm account and \"[[scrobble]]\" them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.last.fm/2012/01/06/scrobble-with-deezer|title=Last.fm \u2013 the Blog \u00b7 Scrobble with Deezer|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Accounts and subscriptions==\nAs of March 2019 there are 6 Deezer account types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deezer.com/en/offers|title=Plans|website=Deezer|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> All subscriptions feature unlimited track playing and support for mobile devices. The Discovery tier only has access to the Playlist/Artist Mix and Flow features on mobile devices.\n\n===Quality===\nSome titles are also available in [[FLAC]] for pay.<ref>{{cite web |title=Deezer HiFi - Unlimited Music Streaming in High Fidelity |url=http://www.deezer.com/en/offers/hifi |website=Deezer |accessdate=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Subscription\n! Price\n! Ads\n! Skipping and [[Scrubbing (audio)|Scrubbing]]\n! Offline Mode\n! TV, HiFi, and Car Support\n! [[Chromecast|Google Chromecast]] Support\n!Accounts\n! Audio Quality (kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Free\n| Free\n| {{No|Ad-Supported}}\n| {{No|Six Skips per Hour, No Scrubbing}}\n| {{No|Unavailable}}\n| {{Yes|Available (Restricted)}}\n| {{Yes|Available (Restricted)}}\n|1\n| MP3 Quality (128 kbit/s)\n|-\n!Deezer Student\n|$4.99/month, 30-day free trial| $4.99, 30-day free trial\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|1\n|MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Premium\n| $9.99/month 30-day free trial\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|1\n| MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Family\n|$14.99/month\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|6\n|MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n!Deezer Annual\n|$99.90 ($8.32/month)\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n|1\n|MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n!Deezer HiFi\n|$19.99, 90-day free trial| $14.99, 90-day free trial\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n|1\n|CD Quality (16-bit 1,411 kbps)\n|}\n\n==Available devices==\nDeezer is available via:\n*[[Apple Watch]]\n*[[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n*[[Android TV]]\n*[[Amazon Echo]]\n*[[Amazon Alexa]]\n*[[Amazon Fire TV]]\n*[[Bang & Olufsen]] \n* Bluesound Network Player\n* [[BMW|BMW ConnectedDrive]]\n* [[Bose Corporation|Bose Music]]\n*[[Control4]]\n*[[Devialet]]\n*[[Facebook Portal]]\n*[[Fitbit]]\n* [[Chromecast|Google Chromecast]]\n* [[Google Home]]\n*[[Garmin]]\n*[[HEOS by Denon]]\n* [[Harman Kardon]] \n*[[iOS]] \n*LG Music Flow\n*[[WebOS|LG WebOS]] \n*[[macOS]]\n*[[Mini (marque)|MINI]] Connected\n*Moon by Simaudio\n*[[Onkyo]] Network A/V Receivers\n*[[Panasonic]] TV\n* [[Philips]] TV\n* [[Roku]]\n*[[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]] Multiroom Wireless Audio Speakers\n* [[Samsung Smart TV]]\n* [[Sonos|Sonos Audio Systems]]\n*[[Sony Bravia]]\n*[[Sony]] High Definition Audio Range\n*Uconnect Live\n*[[Ultimate Ears]]\n*[[Waze]]\n*[[Wear OS|Wear OS by Google]]\n*[[Windows 7]]\n* [[Windows 8]] \n* [[Windows 10]] \n*[[Windows 10 Mobile]]\n*[[Xbox One]]\n* [[Yamaha]] A/V Receivers with MusicCast - 2017 models and up\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of streaming media systems]]\n* [[Comparison of on-demand music streaming services]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.deezer.com/}}\n\n{{Music streaming services}}\n\n[[Category:French music websites]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:Windows Phone software]]\n[[Category:Symbian software]]\n[[Category:Universal Windows Platform apps]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Web-based music streaming service}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Deezer\n| logo             = [[File:Deezer logo.svg|250px]]\n| company_type     = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2007|8|df=yes}}<br>[[Paris]], [[France]]\n| location_city    = Paris, [[\u00cele-de-France]]\n| location_country = France<ref name=\"legal\">{{cite web|url= http://www.deezer.com/legal/legal |title= Deezer.com legal |accessdate= 2015-12-06}}</ref>\n| founder          = Daniel Marhely<br>Jonathan Benassaya\n| key_people       = Hans-Holger Albrecht<ref name=press /> ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])<br>Laurent Cordonnier ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])<br> Daniel Marhely ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| services         = [[Streaming media|Music streaming]]\n| industry         = Music, podcast, and video\n| owner            = \n| parent           = [[Access Industries]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7502855/deezer-access-industries-french-approval-len-blavatnik |title=Warner Music's Parent Company Now In Control of Deezer Following French Approval |magazine=Billboard |date=9 August 2016 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xAsiHkrR?url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7502855/deezer-access-industries-french-approval-len-blavatnik |archivedate=12 February 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><br><small>(2016\u2013present)</small>\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.deezer.com/}}\n| alexa            = {{Increase}} 1,529 ({{As of|2019|02|28|alt=February 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |title=Deezer.com Traffic, Demographics and Competitors - Alexa |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/deezer.com |website=www.alexa.com |accessdate=28 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| commercial       = Yes\n| registration     = Required\n| num_users        =\n| language         = 180+ countries<ref name=\"press\">{{cite web| url= http://www.deezer.com/company/press | title= Deezer press page show company stats | accessdate= 2015-12-06}}</ref>\n| current_status   = Active\n| native_clients   = [[World Wide Web|Web]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Mobile]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[MacOS]]\n}}\n\n'''Deezer''' is a French online [[music streaming service]]. It allows users to listen to music content from record labels, including [[Universal Music Group]], [[Sony Music]] and [[Warner Music Group]] (owned by Deezer's parent company [[Access Industries]]) on various devices online or offline. Created in [[Paris]], [[France]], Deezer currently has 56 million licensed tracks in its library, with over 30,000 radio channels, 14 million [[monthly active users]], and 7 million paid subscribers as of January 2019.<ref name=\"deezer.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deezer.com/company|title=About us|work=Deezer}}</ref>  The service is available for Web, [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Windows Mobile]], [[BlackBerry OS]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[MacOS]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Deezer.svg|thumb|250px|First logo of Deezer.]]\nIn 2006, Daniel Marhely developed the first version of Deezer, called Blogmusik, in Paris. His idea was to give unlimited access to music lovers through [[streaming media|streaming]] technology.\n\nThe site in its original incarnation was charged with copyright infringement by French agency [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des auteurs, compositeurs et \u00e9diteurs de musique|SACEM]], and after being shut down in April 2007<ref name=\"ina\"/> was relaunched as Deezer in August 2007, having reached an agreement with SACEM to pay copyright holders with revenue from advertising on the site<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/08/21/blogmusik-comes-back-with-a-legal-free-music-on-demand-service/ |title=Exclusive: BlogMusik To Go Legit; Launches Free & Legal Music On Demand |work=TechCrunch |date=21 August 2007 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5G9jSiv?url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/08/21/blogmusik-comes-back-with-a-legal-free-music-on-demand-service/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and by giving users the ability to download songs streamed on Deezer from [[iTunes]], with Deezer receiving a commission from each purchase.<ref name=\"ina\"/>\n\n===Launch===\nAt the time of its launch in 2007, Deezer had not yet negotiated agreements with major music labels and therefore offered a limited catalogue.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  It took more than two years for agreements to be signed with the four largest labels, as well as various smaller ones, but by 2011 the company had rights to about eight million songs.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  During August 2007, its first month of operations, Deezer saw about 773,000 visitors to its site, with traffic increasing rapidly in the next several years\u20142.75 million people used the service in May 2008, and there were seven million users by December 2009.<ref name=\"ina\"/>\n\nDespite the high traffic, Deezer almost immediately ran into financial problems\u2014during the first half of 2008, the company saw revenue of just 875,000 euros, not enough to pay its licensing fees.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  In July 2008, the company began running ads itself through advertising agency Deezer Media; in October, Deezer secured $8.4 million in funding from AGF Private Equity and CM-CIC Capital Prive, bringing total investment in the company to $15.8 million.<ref name=\"wsj oct 2012\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/tech-europe/2012/10/08/deezers-expansion-plans-get-a-boost/ | title=Deezer\u2019s Expansion Plans Get a Boost | newspaper=Wall Street Journal | date=8 October 2012 | accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> The company introduced mandatory registration in February 2009 to gather more precise data on users, in order to run more targeted ads, and in November 2009 began running audio ads between songs.<ref name=\"ina\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inaglobal.fr/en/music/article/deezer-profitability-down-line |title=Deezer: Profitability Down the Line? |publisher=INA Global |date=19 August 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403164334/http://www.inaglobal.fr/en/music/article/deezer-profitability-down-line?tq=4 |archivedate=3 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November 2009, Deezer launched a new three-tier service model.  While continuing basic free web streaming, the company also introduced two subscription services\u2014users paying \u20ac4.99 monthly received higher-quality music without ads, and users paying \u20ac9.99 monthly gained access to downloadable applications for computers, as well as [[Android (operating system)|Android]],  [[BlackBerry]], and [[iOS]] mobile devices.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/11/05/digital-music-startup-deezer-debuts-desktop-client-premium-offering/ |title=Digital music startup Deezer debuts desktop client, premium offering |work=TechCrunch |date=5 November 2009 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5I10EIt?url=https://techcrunch.com/2009/11/05/digital-music-startup-deezer-debuts-desktop-client-premium-offering/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, the company's CEO and co-founder, Jonathan Benassaya, was replaced as CEO by Axel Dauchez, after fewer than 15,000 of Deezer's 12 million users signed up for its subscription services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/28/post-bloodletting-deezer-appoints-a-new-ceo/ |title=Post bloodletting, Deezer appoints a new CEO |work=TechCrunch |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5ItPrqj?url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/28/post-bloodletting-deezer-appoints-a-new-ceo/ |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>  In August 2010, mobile operator [[Orange S.A.|Orange]] partnered with Deezer in a deal to include free access to Deezer Premium, the highest tier of Deezer's streaming packages, with some of Orange's telecommunications contracts in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendigest.com/news/orange-brings-deezer-premium-to-its-customers/view.html |title=Orange brings Deezer Premium to its customers |publisher=Screen Digest |date=6 August 2010 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5JgHziH?url=http://www.screendigest.com/news/orange-brings-deezer-premium-to-its-customers/view.html |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Almost immediately after the partnership began, the rate of users signing up for Deezer's premium services went from 6,000 a month to 100,000; by January 2011, 500,000 people were subscribing to the service, with the million-subscriber mark reached in the middle of 2011, half a year ahead of schedule.<ref name=\"ina\"/>  The two companies expanded their partnership in September 2011 to include Orange contract customers in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/66bdfd5c-d939-11e0-bd7e-00144feabdc0.html |title=Deezer takes on Spotify with Orange deal |newspaper=Financial Times |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5JROpX1?url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/66bdfd5c-d939-11e0-bd7e-00144feabdc0.html |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Also in September, Deezer added [[Facebook]] integration to its service, allowing users to send music to one another via that social media service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/deezer-enters-realm-of-facebook--828792 |title=Deezer enters realm of Facebook |publisher=Telecompaper |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D5K0dI3g?url=http://www.telecompaper.com/news/deezer-enters-realm-of-facebook--828792 |archivedate=21 December 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Expansion to more countries===\n[[File:Availability of Deezer in the World.svg|thumb|350px|Availability of Deezer in the world {{as of|2016|8|lc=on}}.]]\nDeezer was launched in France in 2007, where it was the market leader as of 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sophie Sassard |title=Deezer: The French music streaming service taking on Spotify, Apple and Amazon |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/deezer-music-streaming-spotify-amazon-apple-subscritpiton-hans-holger-albrecht-len-blavatnik-a7940896.html |accessdate=27 December 2018 |work=The Independent |date=20 September 2017 |quote=The unlisted company, which launched a decade ago, is the market leader in its home market of France}}</ref> On 7 December 2011, Deezer, at the time available only in Belgium, France and the United Kingdom, announced plans to expand worldwide during the rest of 2011 and continuing into 2012.<ref name=\"tech dec 2011\"/> According to the company, it planned to make its services available to the whole of Europe by the end of the year, to the Americas (excluding the United States) by the end of January 2012, to Africa and Southeast Asia by the end of February, and the rest of the world (excluding Japan) by the end of June.<ref name=\"tech dec 2011\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/12/07/deezer-plans-to-launch-in-200-countries-by-june-2012-but-not-in-the-usa/|title=Deezer plans to launch music service in 200 countries by June 2012 (but not in the US and Japan)|work=TechCrunch|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt took until 15 March 2012 for service to be available across the whole of Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/eu/2012/03/15/deezer-now-covers-all-european-countries-from-iceland-to-russia-46-countries/|title=Deezer now covers all European countries from Iceland to Russia (46 countries)|work=The Next Web| date=15 March 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> while service launched in Australia, Canada, and New Zealand on 25 April.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2012/04/25/spotify-rival-deezer-launches-in-canada-australia-and-new-zealand-still-noticeably-absent-from-the-us/| title=Spotify rival Deezer continues its worldwide expansion with the launch in Canada, Australia, and New Zealand|work=The Next Web|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> On 8 June, Deezer announced availability in 35 Latin American countries, though not in Brazil, Cuba, or Venezuela.<ref name=\"tnw lat am\">{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/la/2012/06/07/music-streaming-service-deezer-goes-live-in-35-latin-american-territories-today/|title=Music streaming service Deezer goes live in 35 Latin American territories today|work=The Next Web|date=7 June 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  On 15 August, Deezer announced it would be available in Indonesia, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand within several weeks.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/08/15/european-music-streaming-service-deezer-heads-to-asia-partners-with-telco-dtac-in-thailand/|title=European Music Streaming Service Deezer Heads to Asia; Partners With Telco dTac In Thailand |work=TechCrunch|date=15 August 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2012, Deezer announced that it had received $130 million in funding from [[Access Industries]], to be used for further international expansion.<ref name=\"wsj oct 2012\"/>  Two days later, the company announced that it had expanded into 76 new markets, bringing its worldwide total to 160 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/10/10/3482702/deezer-expansion-160-countries-no-us-plans|title=Deezer's streaming music service now available in 160 countries, US market 'not ready'|work=The Verge|date=10 October 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  On 21 December, Deezer announced a new service level offering two hours of free, ad-supported music streaming a month, available to users worldwide, the company's first free music streaming service outside France.<ref name=\"wsj dec 2012\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324461604578191043343259734|title=Spotify Rival Deezer Eyes U.S|work=Wall Street Journal|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>  CEO Dauchez said that Deezer was also looking for a partner to introduce service in the United States, who was \"able to provide us with a significant volume of subscribers\" to help offset what he called the \"unbelievably high\" costs of entering the US market.<ref name=\"wsj dec 2012\"/>\n\nAs of December 2012, Deezer had about two million users paying for subscriptions, out of a monthly active user base of about seven million, with 20 million songs in its library.<ref name=\"tech interview\"/>  By 2016, according to CEO Dauchez, the company aimed to have five percent of the global music market.<ref name=\"tech interview\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/09/deezer-ceo-streaming-music/|title=Deezer\u2019s CEO Axel Dauchez On Cracking Into The U.S. And Why It\u2019s Not Just Another Spotify|work=TechCrunch|date=9 October 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Deezer announced its expansion into 22 new countries across Africa, Asia, Brazil,  the [[Middle East]], and the [[United States]], bringing its total to 182.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/01/28/deezer-takes-on-spotify-with-expansions-in-middle-east-africa-brazil-and-asia/|title=Deezer Takes On Spotify With Expansions In Middle East, Africa, Brazil And Asia|work=TechCrunch|date=28 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.challenges.fr/high-tech/20131120.CHA7207/deezer-compte-se-lancer-aux-etats-unis-en-2014.html Deezer compte se lancer aux Etats-Unis en 2014], ''Challenges'', 20 November 2013</ref> However, the United States launch has been restricted to a limited number of device promotions.<ref>[http://www.cnet.com/news/deezer-entering-us-will-sound-like-spotify-act-like-netflix/ Deezer, entering US] www.cnet.com. Retrieved on 2016-01-23.</ref> In July 2016, Deezer added the U.S. to the supported country list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deezer Music Preview for Windows 10 PC and Mobile is now available for U.S. users|url=http://m.windowscentral.com/deezer-preview-windows-10-pc-and-mobile-now-available-us-users|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref>  As of February 2018, Deezer listed on its website 189 countries where the service was available.<ref>[http://developers.deezer.com/guidelines/countries Deezer for developers]. Developers.deezer.com. Retrieved on 2018-02-28.</ref>\n\n===After expansion===\nFollowing this expansion, Deezer announced in 2013 partnerships with [[LG Electronics]], [[Samsung Electronics]], and [[Toshiba]] that saw Deezer apps made available on smart TV platforms,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/02/06/deezer-is-to-bring-its-streaming-music-service-to-smart-tvs-via-deals-with-samsung-lg-and-toshiba/ | title=Deezer is bringing its streaming music service to smart TVs, via deals with Samsung, LG and Toshiba | accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> along with a new brand identity developed in association with the illustrator mcbess.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.designweek.co.uk/we-like/mcbess-draws-for-deezer/3035958.article| title=McBess draws for Deezer | accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSince then, Deezer has made a number of announcements, including its Developer Reward Scheme, mobile App Studio, and API upgrades,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2013/03/13/music-streaming-service-deezer-adds-app-discovery-to-smartphones-brings-app-activity-to-its-social-bar/?fromcat=all| title=Music streaming service Deezer adds third-party app discovery to smartphones, updates its API | publisher=The Next Web |accessdate=13 March 2013}}</ref> a new, exclusive beta version of its mobile app for Android users,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/04/03/deezer-for-android-beta/| title=Deezer for Android gets a redesign, predictive search function in new beta version | publisher=Engadget |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> and the new Deezer app for [[Windows 8]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2013/04/17/deezer-launches-a-windows-8-app-for-its-on-demand-streaming-music-service-ahead-of-spotify-and-rdio/?fromcat=all| title=Deezer launches Windows 8 app for its on-demand music streaming service ahead of Spotify and Rdio | publisher=The Next Web |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nApril 2013 also saw Deezer update its iOS app with a new smart caching feature, allowing the app to identify and remember a user's most played tracks, even in areas of poor network coverage.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://musically.com/2013/04/26/deezer-adds-smart-caching-to-its-ios-app/| title=Deezer adds \u2018smart caching\u2019 to its iOS app | publisher=Music Ally |accessdate=26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Deezer announced a new partnership with [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]] giving [[Samsung Galaxy S5]] users in Europe a free, six months Deezer Premium+ subscription. Samsung and Deezer extended their partnership by offering a six-month, free of charge subscription to Deezer Premium+ for Samsung's Multiroom Wireless Audio Products, including its M5 and M7 line of Multiroom wireless audio speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/items/entertainment/70726-six-months-music-free-samsung-deezer/|title=Six months of music free from Samsung and Deezer|website=HEXUS|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> Samsung UK and Deezer offered this promotion again from 2016-2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samsung.com/uk/offer/deezer/|title=Up to 2 years of music when you buy two or more selected Multiroom products|website=Samsung uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currys.co.uk/gbuk/deezer-1346-commercial.html|title=How to claim your complimentary Deezer Premium+ {{!}} Currys|website=www.currys.co.uk|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Deezer and Google announced that the Google [[Chromecast]] would be supporting Deezer's Android and [[iPhone]] apps to allow users to stream music from their phone to their televisions through the Chromecast. Chromecast support became available to Deezer Premium+ users from 25 June 2014 onwards in Australia, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Finland, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, South Korea, Spain, Sweden,  Switzerland, and the United Kingdom. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn September 2014, Deezer announced Deezer Elite, a new exclusive service made for and in partnership with [[Sonos]]. Deezer Elite provides CD-quality audio to U.S. users of [[Sonos]] Hi-Fi Systems. The service is available worldwide to Sonos users of Deezer only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/exceptional-audio-quality-with-deezer-elite-and-sonos/|title=Exceptional audio quality with Deezer Elite and Sonos|work=deezer.com}}</ref> Deezer Elite \"High-Resolution Audio\" is lossless CD quality (16bit/44.1&nbsp;kHz) and not \"Hi-Res\" or [[high-resolution audio]]. Sonos does not support Hi-Res (24/96, 24/192 or similar) streaming.\n\nDeezer HiFi offers 36 million tracks of 16-Bit/44.1&nbsp;kHz of FLAC quality music for a $19.95 monthly subscription in the United States. It is \"Only available on selected soundsystems and the Desktop App,\u201d and offers downloads to phones at 320 kbit/s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deezer.com/en/offers/hifi|title=Deezer HiFi|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer rolled out a new user interface for its website player. This new change in design was widely welcomed by numerous users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/our-smart-new-look/|title=Our smart new look|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer announced that [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] SoundTouch and SoundLink products would now be supported for Deezer Premium+ service. This partnership will first be rolled out in the United States and then will be available to worldwide users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.deezer.com/u-s-music-fans-can-now-enjoy-deezer-premium-via-bose-products/|title=U.S. music fans can now enjoy Deezer Premium+ on Bose products|work=deezer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Deezer announced that [[Stitcher Radio]] would be merging into Deezer. By 2015, Deezer users would be able to use Stitcher Radio features within Deezer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stitcher.com/blog/?p=1588|title=Stitcher joins Deezer! \u00ab  Stitcher Blog|work=stitcher.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Deezer and Pepsi announced a partnership to set up the Midem Artist Accelerator to support managers and labels as they grow the profiles of their artists.<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hottopics.ht/stories/consumer/deezer-talks-streaming-music |title= Deezer: bring on the competition, there are 3.47bn more streaming music consumers to go round |publisher=Hot Topics |date=9 January 2015 |first=Tim |last=Green |accessdate=14 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"musically\">{{cite web|url=http://musically.com/2014/12/20/midem-pepsi-deezer-team-artist-accelerator/ |title=Midem, Pepsi, and Deezer team up for 'artist accelerator' |publisher=musically |date=20 December 2014 |accessdate=14 January 2015 }}</ref> In   June 2016, it sold Stitcher to [[E.W. Scripps Company]] for $4.5 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/scripps-buys-stitcher-1201789683/|title=Scripps Buys Podcast Service Stitcher from Deezer|first=Janko|last=Roettgers|date=6 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Deezer integrated [[Triton Digital]] to monetize the free users with programmatic audio ads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ppc.land/deezer-audio-ads-now-available-via-triton-digital/|title=Deezer audio ads now available via Triton Digital|date=2018-12-13|website=PPC Land|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref> Deezer also pushes banner advertisements for WAZE, even for premium subscribers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAt November 7, 2019, Deezer released Spleeter, an open-source \"audio source separation\" utility written in [[Python (programming language)|Python]] that uses the [[TensorFlow]] machine learning library and pretrained models for audio \"stem\" extraction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deezer.io/releasing-spleeter-deezer-r-d-source-separation-engine-2b88985e797e|title=Releasing Spleeter: Deezer R&D source separation engine|last=Moussallam|first=Manuel|date=2019-11-04|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Last.fm  integration==\nIn January 2012, [[Last.fm]] announced that Deezer would integrate with [[Last.fm]], allowing users to send songs from Deezer to their Last.fm account and \"[[scrobble]]\" them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.last.fm/2012/01/06/scrobble-with-deezer|title=Last.fm \u2013 the Blog \u00b7 Scrobble with Deezer|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Accounts and subscriptions==\nAs of March 2019 there are 6 Deezer account types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deezer.com/en/offers|title=Plans|website=Deezer|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> All subscriptions feature unlimited track playing and support for mobile devices. The Discovery tier only has access to the Playlist/Artist Mix and Flow features on mobile devices.\n\n===Quality===\nSome titles are also available in [[FLAC]] for pay.<ref>{{cite web |title=Deezer HiFi - Unlimited Music Streaming in High Fidelity |url=http://www.deezer.com/en/offers/hifi |website=Deezer |accessdate=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Subscription\n! Price\n! Ads\n! Skipping and [[Scrubbing (audio)|Scrubbing]]\n! Offline Mode\n! TV, HiFi, and Car Support\n! [[Chromecast|Google Chromecast]] Support\n!Accounts\n! Audio Quality (kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Free\n| Free\n| {{No|Ad-Supported}}\n| {{No|Six Skips per Hour, No Scrubbing}}\n| {{No|Unavailable}}\n| {{Yes|Available (Restricted)}}\n| {{Yes|Available (Restricted)}}\n|1\n| MP3 Quality (128 kbit/s)\n|-\n!Deezer Student\n|$4.99/month, 30-day free trial| $4.99, 30-day free trial\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|1\n|MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Premium\n| $9.99/month 30-day free trial\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|1\n| MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n! Deezer Family\n|$14.99/month\n| {{Yes|None}}\n| {{Yes|Unlimited Skips and Scrubbing}}\n| {{Yes|Available|Unknown number of devices}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n| {{Yes|Available}}\n|6\n|MP3 Quality (320 kbit/s)\n|-\n!Deezer Annual\